labels.name: api: firestore
labels.description: Issues related to the googleapis/python-firestore API.

labels.name: type: process

items.body: The systests expect to have `FIRESTORE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS` set, but the templated `.kokoro/build.sh` is setting only the more normal `GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS`.  The [monorepo `.kokoro/build.sh` set both](https://github.com/googleapis/google-cloud-python/blob/0d8b70a2bd6a279fa5e172b182006c7038491521/.kokoro/build.sh#L27-L31).

items.title: Cannot query by document id

labels.name: api: firestore
labels.description: Issues related to the googleapis/python-firestore API.

labels.name: priority: p2
labels.description: Moderately-important priority. Fix may not be included in next release.

labels.name: type: bug
labels.description: Error or flaw in code with unintended results or allowing sub-optimal usage patterns.

items.body:
Apparently, at the moment there is no functioning python client which can filter query results by document id. To my understanding, this should work by simply putting `__name__` as field value in any where/order clause like in this example:

```
from google.cloud import firestore_v1

db = firestore_v1.Client()

# query user data
query = db.collection('users').where(firestore_v1.field_path.FieldPath.document_id(), '==', '...').stream()
dicts = []
for doc in query:
  dicts.append(doc.to_dict())
 
print(dicts)
```

However, this code will throw the following exception:
```
__key__ filter value must be a Key
```

items.title: Separate constructor invalid path test cases

labels.name: api: firestore
labels.description: Issues related to the googleapis/python-firestore API.

labels.name: priority: p1
labels.description: Important issue which blocks shipping the next release. Will be fixed prior to next release.

items.body:
Current [constructor tests](https://github.com/googleapis/python-firestore/blob/master/tests/unit/v1/test_collection.py#L64-L72) test multiple failure conditions in one test case. By separating these tests into multiple test cases it will be more clear which failure is the cause.

```
def test_constructor_invalid_path(self):
    with self.assertRaises(ValueError):
        self._make_one()
    with self.assertRaises(ValueError):
        self._make_one(99, "doc", "bad-collection-id")
    with self.assertRaises(ValueError):
        self._make_one("bad-document-ID", None, "sub-collection")
    with self.assertRaises(ValueError):
        self._make_one("Just", "A-Document")
```

items.title: export_documents return type changed between 1.7.0 and 1.8.1

labels.name: api: firestore
labels.description: Issues related to the googleapis/python-firestore API.

labels.name: type: question
labels.description: Request for information or clarification. Not an issue.

items.body:
Hi, I'm using export_documents to backup Firestore, and I've found that the return type seems to have changed between 1.7.0 and 1.8.1.  Is this intentional?

With 1.7.0 it returns an with `metadata` and `name` properties (edit: I think this is an instance of `google.longrunning.operations_pb2.Operation`?).
With 1.8.1 it returns an instance of `google.api_core.operation.Operation` that has a property `operation`, with those properties - so it seems like the result from 1.7.0 is nested in the result from 1.8.1.

#### Environment details

  - OS type and version:

Ubuntu 20.04

  - Python version: `python --version`

3.7.7

  - pip version: `pip --version`

19.2.3

  - `google-cloud-firestore` version: `pip show google-cloud-firestore`

1.7.0 vs 1.8.1

#### Steps to reproduce

See example code below, this works with client package 1.7.0, but fails with 1.8.1

#### Code example

```python
import os

from google.cloud.firestore_admin_v1.gapic import firestore_admin_client
from google.api_core.operations_v1 import operations_client
from google.api_core import operation as core_operation
from google.cloud.firestore_admin_v1.proto import operation_pb2


project_id = os.environ["GOOGLE_CLOUD_PROJECT"]
output_bucket_name = os.environ["OUTPUT_BUCKET_NAME"]

client = firestore_admin_client.FirestoreAdminClient()
name = client.database_path(project_id, "(default)")
output_uri_prefix = f"gs://{output_bucket_name}"

print("start operation")

operation = client.export_documents(
  name=name,
  output_uri_prefix=output_uri_prefix,
)

print(f"operation is a {operation.__class__.__name__} = {operation}")

operation_client = operations_client.OperationsClient(
  client.transport.channel)

operation_future = core_operation.from_gapic(
      operation,
      operation_client,
      operation_pb2.ExportDocumentsResponse,
      metadata_type=operation_pb2.ExportDocumentsMetadata,
  )

print("await operation completion")

# Block until the operation has completed if it's not already done
operation_future.result()

print("done")
```

#### Stack trace

```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/home/johnc/.config/JetBrains/PyCharm2020.1/scratches/scratch_23.py", line 32, in <module>
    metadata_type=operation_pb2.ExportDocumentsMetadata,
  File "/home/johnc/.cache/pypoetry/virtualenvs/gweb-digital-guru-aZuuZtrT-py3.7/lib/python3.7/site-packages/google/api_core/operation.py", line 325, in from_gapic
    refresh = functools.partial(operations_client.get_operation, operation.name)
AttributeError: 'Operation' object has no attribute 'name'
```

items.title: Refactor to generalize classes

labels.name: api: firestore
labels.description: Issues related to the googleapis/python-firestore API.

labels.name: priority: p1
labels.description: Important issue which blocks shipping the next release. Will be fixed prior to next release.

labels.name: type: feature request
labels.description: ‘Nice-to-have’ improvement, new feature or different behavior or design.

items.body:
Refactor classes with the intent of adding async support. Refactor will enable future async classes to inherit sync functions and constants with minimal duplication in implementation and testers.

This refactor can generally be described as creating a `Base` counterpart (eg. `BaseClient` for `Client`) that takes all of the sync requirements, while `Client` inherits from `BaseClient` and implements functions that have reason to be async in an async implementation. The intention is to allow the addition of the async feature to have minimal impact on the existing implementation. This change allows us to inherit the bare minimum functionality for async classes while keeping testing streamlined and straightforward.

items.body:
I am using version 1.6.2, and lost quite a while to debugging why the issue fixed in this commit was causing my code to fail:
https://github.com/googleapis/python-firestore/commit/de3aca0e78b68f66eb76bc679c6e95b0746ad590

Until that's fixed, transactions are much more clumsy to work with than intended.

items.title: Firestore: Problem with pagination with "in" query

labels.name: api: firestore
labels.description: Issues related to the googleapis/python-firestore API.

labels.name: type: question
labels.description: Request for information or clarification. Not an issue.

items.body:
Hi Folks,
Trying to implement pagination with "in" query raise the following error: `"order by clause cannot contain a field with an equality filter category"`

#### Environment details


OS type and version: `Mac OS X - 10.15.3` and also `AppEngine`
3. Python version and virtual environment information: `Python 3.7.5`
4. google-cloud-firestore version:  `1.6.2`

#### Steps to reproduce

  1. Just try to have query with "start_at" (or "start_after") and a "in" query.

#### Code example

```python
def firestore_pagination_in_query_problem(db):

    # Setup test data.
    for i in range(10):
        db.collection("test-data").document().create({"category": "c1"})

    # First Query.
    results = [
        snapshot
        for snapshot in db.collection("test-data")
        .limit(4)
        .where("category", "in", ["c1"])
        .stream()
    ]
    last_snap = results[-1]

    try:
        # Second Query.
        results = [
            snapshot
            for snapshot in db.collection("test-data")
            .limit(4)
            .where("category", "in", ["c1"])
            .start_at(last_snap)
            .stream()
        ]

    except Exception:
        print_exc()
    finally:
        # Cleanup test data.
        for snapshot in db.collection("test-data").stream():
            snapshot.reference.delete()
```

#### Stack trace
```
grpc._channel._MultiThreadedRendezvous: <_MultiThreadedRendezvous of RPC that terminated with:
	status = StatusCode.INVALID_ARGUMENT
	details = "order by clause cannot contain a field with an equality filter category"
	debug_error_string = "{"created":"@1584605000.505801000","description":"Error received from peer ipv4:[..]:443","file":"src/core/lib/surface/call.cc","file_line":1056,"grpc_message":"order by clause cannot contain a field with an equality filter category","grpc_status":3}"
```

items.title: inconsistent type annotations for Document.on_snapshot

labels.name: api: firestore
labels.description: Issues related to the googleapis/python-firestore API.

labels.name: type: docs
labels.description: Improvement to the documentation for an API.

items.body:
Looking here (which mirrors the API docs):
https://github.com/googleapis/python-firestore/blob/de3aca0e78b68f66eb76bc679c6e95b0746ad590/google/cloud/firestore_v1/document.py#L503-L504

The claim is that the callback invoked by `on_snapshot` should have type signature `Callable[[:class:`~google.cloud.firestore.document.DocumentSnapshot`], NoneType]`. however, just a few lines lower, in the example, it looks like the callback receives three arguments: https://github.com/googleapis/python-firestore/blob/de3aca0e78b68f66eb76bc679c6e95b0746ad590/google/cloud/firestore_v1/document.py#L515

i tried to understand what's going on by reading the code, and didn't make too much progress. we invoke the callback here: https://github.com/googleapis/python-firestore/blob/de3aca0e78b68f66eb76bc679c6e95b0746ad590/google/cloud/firestore_v1/watch.py#L569-L573

it looks like there are indeed three arguments passed. `appliedChanges` appears to be a `List[DocumentChange]`, and the final argument seems to be a `datetime.datetime` instance. but the first argument... is the result of calling `keys()` on a `document_tree` (here: https://github.com/googleapis/python-firestore/blob/de3aca0e78b68f66eb76bc679c6e95b0746ad590/google/cloud/firestore_v1/watch.py#L567) and so maybe is a `List[str]` ? the `self.doc_tree` is an instance of `WatchDocTree` and it's `keys()` method returns the underlying dict's keys. are those keys actually `DocumentSnapshot` instances? it maybe sort of seems like it, after tracing through the code a bunch. i'm *guessing* that the correct type signature for the callback is:

```
Callable[List[DocumentSnapshot], List[DocumentChange], datetime.datime], None]
```

but it would be nice if this was confirmed, and the documentation updated to reflect reality.

items.title: Support tuple when encoding to Firestore value

labels.name: api: firestore
labels.description: Issues related to the googleapis/python-firestore API.

labels.name: type: feature request
labels.description: ‘Nice-to-have’ improvement, new feature or different behavior or design.

items.body:
Thanks for stopping by to let us know something could be better!

 **Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
When I save data to Firestore, it reject when the data contains tuple.

```py
  File "/env/local/lib/python3.7/site-packages/google/cloud/firestore_v1/_helpers.py", line 200, in encode_value
    "Cannot convert to a Firestore Value", value, "Invalid type", type(value)
TypeError: ('Cannot convert to a Firestore Value', (1, 12), 'Invalid type', <class 'tuple'>)
```
 **Describe the solution you'd like**

It should accept `tuple`. This is pragmatic because when I decide to submit data to Firestore, I no longer need to modify the content, so I leave it in a immutable type like `tuple`.

 **Describe alternatives you've considered**
Change the `encode_value()` function:

```py
    if isinstance(value, list):
        value_list = [encode_value(element) for element in value]
```
to this

```py
    if isinstance(value, (list, tuple, set, frozenset)):
        value_list = tuple(encode_value(element) for element in value)
```
 **Additional context**
Add any other context or screenshots about the feature request here.

items.title: Firestore: Can't get data in transaction.get call

labels.name: api: firestore
labels.description: Issues related to the googleapis/python-firestore API.

labels.name: priority: p2
labels.description: Moderately-important priority. Fix may not be included in next release.

labels.name: type: bug
labels.description: Error or flaw in code with unintended results or allowing sub-optimal usage patterns.

items.body:
#### Environment details

1. Specify the API at the beginning of the title: Firestore
2. OS type and version: MacOS 10.15.2
3. Python version and virtual environment information: `python --version`: Python 3.7.4
4. google-cloud-<service> version:  `pip show google-<service>` or `pip freeze`: google-cloud-firestore==1.6.1

#### Steps to reproduce

  1. Create a document in your firestore database.
  2. Run the code below, which will raise an `AttributeError: 'bytes' object has no attribute 'in_progress'`.

#### Code example

```python
transaction = db.transaction()
doc_ref = ... # get a reference to the document you created in step 1 above

@firestore.transactional
def update_in_transaction(transaction, doc_ref):
    docs = transaction.get(doc_ref)
    for doc in docs:
        print(doc)
```

#### Stack trace
```
# Abbreviated stack trace
  File ".../venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/google/cloud/firestore_v1/client.py", line 440, in get_all
    transaction=_helpers.get_transaction_id(transaction),
  File ".../venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/google/cloud/firestore_v1/_helpers.py", line 934, in get_transaction_id
    if not transaction.in_progress:
AttributeError: 'bytes' object has no attribute 'in_progress'
```

#### Additional Notes
It appears the helper function `get_transaction_id` is expecting a `Transaction` object, but both the `Transaction.get()` and `Transaction.get_all()` calls are passing a `Transaction._id`. 

When I changed line 230 of transaction.py from:
`return ref_or_query.stream(transaction=self._id)`
to:
`return ref_or_query.stream(transaction=self)`

It appears to fix the issue.

items.title: Firestore: SSLError(OSError(24, 'Too many open files')

labels.name: :rotating_light:
labels.description: This issue needs some love.

labels.name: api: firestore
labels.description: Issues related to the googleapis/python-firestore API.

labels.name: priority: p2
labels.description: Moderately-important priority. Fix may not be included in next release.

labels.name: type: bug
labels.description: Error or flaw in code with unintended results or allowing sub-optimal usage patterns.

items.body:
I'm using the firestore module within a Flask application. 

I'm receiving the following error: 
SSLError(OSError(24, 'Too many open files')

It seems that the json permission file which is used by the Firestore Client never gets closed and therefore I always bounce against this limit.

I can offcourse increase this limit using 'ulimit' but then I'm just postponing the error. I already saw that this issue was fixed for the grpc client (which you can now close after your call) but it seems that this is not possible atm for this concerning Client.

I've already tried killing the Client object itself (using del ) but this does not seem to fix the problem.

Thanks in advance for helping me out

Cheers

Cedric

items.title: Firestore: allow field paths to start with a number

labels.name: api: firestore
labels.description: Issues related to the googleapis/python-firestore API.

labels.name: type: question
labels.description: Request for information or clarification. Not an issue.

items.body:
So I just realized that if I have a document like:
```
{
   "0foo": "text",
   "bar": "text"
}

```
This will work:
`doc_ref.get()`

This will work:
`doc_ref.get(["bar"])`

And this will not because the field path begins with a number:
`doc_ref.get(["0foo"])`
... and resulting in a `google.api_core.exceptions.InvalidArgument: 400 Invalid property path "0foo"`.

What I dont understand is why I would even be allowed to create documents with these fields, and only first get an error trying to partially retrieve the documents. I feel like this should already give an error `doc_ref.set(set_dict)`.

I let the admin sdk generate the documents id with `ref.document()`, sometimes I will have a document with references to these, or even copies of the document, it is redundant but increases the speed when retrieving collections. In short these documents contains maps with other documents where the key (field path) will be the document id. This document sometimes has a starting number instead of character, which leads to my "bug".

An easy workaround to this will be to generate the documents id differently or check if they have a starting number.

items.title: Firestore API docs do not reflect the released distributions

labels.name: :rotating_light:
labels.description: This issue needs some love.

labels.name: priority: p2
labels.description: Moderately-important priority. Fix may not be included in next release.

labels.name: type: docs
labels.description: Improvement to the documentation for an API.

labels.name: type: feature request
labels.description: ‘Nice-to-have’ improvement, new feature or different behavior or design.

items.body:
API docs for Cloud Firestore seem to be auto-generated from the master branch: https://googleapis.github.io/google-cloud-python/latest/firestore/collection.html#google.cloud.firestore_v1beta1.collection.CollectionReference

This contains several APIs that are not yet available in any of the released distributions (e.g. `stream()`, `list_documents()`).  This often sends developers down the wrong path, that results in Python attribute errors.
